  "prompt": "My pet cat scratched me accidentally.Its not vaccinated and I'm from India. 7 days have passed but the cat is fully well. Do I need anti-rabies shots?",
  "response": "If your cat scratched you and it is not vaccinated against rabies, it is important to assess the potential risk of rabies exposure. In India, rabies is a serious concern, especially in unvaccinated animals. \n\nThe general recommendation in cases of scratches or bites from unvaccinated cats includes considering rabies prophylaxis, especially if the cat shows any signs of illness or if its rabies vaccination status is unknown. Since your cat appears to be well, the immediate risk may be lower, but it's still important to consult a healthcare professional.\n\nHere are some steps to follow:\n\n1. **Clean the wound**: Make sure to thoroughly wash the scratch with soap and water.\n   \n2. **Monitor the cat**: Keep an eye on your cat for any signs of illness for about 10 days. If it remains healthy, it reduces the immediate risk.\n\n3. **Consult a healthcare professional**: Given that the cat is unvaccinated, it's advisable to see a doctor. They will evaluate your risk based on the context and may recommend rabies vaccination.\n\n4. **Follow recommendations**: If advised, get the rabies vaccine and any other necessary treatment.\n\nIt's better to be cautious with potential rabies exposure. Always consult with a medical professional for the most accurate advice tailored to your situation.",
